<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-09-19T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-09-19T06:00:00-05:00" n="180" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d180">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/10171</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SWG1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Sharp</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-09-19T12:00:00+01:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">September 19, 1918—noon.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 1.55 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>5120. War Trade Board [from <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_MG1">McFadden</persName>]:</p>
                            <p>No. 427. The following resolution was adopted by the Inter-Allied
                                Blacklisting Committee, Paris: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                    <p>Inter-Allied Blacklisting, Paris, recognizing the necessity
                                        of complete understanding between the Associated Governments
                                        as to the date of publication of decisions taken both by the
                                        Paris committee and by the committees in London and
                                        Washington, has decided that a delay of ten days shall be
                                        given each Government in which to state if said Government
                                        has any objection to the decisions taken by this committee.
                                        If no objection has been registered before the ten days, the
                                        decisions will become binding and the names decided upon
                                        shall be published in the next bi-weekly lists.</p>
                                </quote>
                            </p>
                            <p>The above resolution was passed as it had been noted by the Paris
                                committee that names adopted at a meeting were not published
                                simultaneously by the Associated Governments. Please instruct if you
                                approve. <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_MG1">McFadden</persName>.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SWG1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sharp</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>